From Errington's response, we see a growing problem for pro-life governments in developing nations in working against population control and abortion:

C. Errington, Professor of Social Anthropology at the University of Edinburgh, pointed out that anti-abortion laws and culture influenced the Mauritian government to provide abortifacient contraceptives, making them easily available and promoting the ‘one child’ policy by make ploicy make the most of what prenatal women are carrying.

A sex-selective abortion has occurred when there is a bias for either gender in the number of births produced. This “sex selection” usually occurs when couples choose to terminate only one gender from a pregnancy.

While male infants are preferred in many parts of the world, sex-selective abortion seems to have risen in persuance with the one-child policy in places such as China.

A sex-selective abortion can also occur when parents or a doctor abort a baby at any stage, solely because of the gender of the child.

In most cultures, we have the sense that every person has value. If sex-selective abortion ever gains momentum, then this attitude may be lost
